abstract: Despite the popularity of liberal policy ideas, voters said in interviews that an incremental approach had a better chance of success.
snippet: Despite the popularity of liberal policy ideas, voters said in interviews that an incremental approach had a better chance of success.
lead_paragraph: There is a puzzle for the Democratic challengers hoping to unseat President Trump, and it is evident in public reaction to some of their breakout policy ideas.

abstract: Candidates condemn President Trump’s “go back” comment, a Harris-Biden rematch, and a new California poll.
snippet: Candidates condemn President Trump’s “go back” comment, a Harris-Biden rematch, and a new California poll.
lead_paragraph: Every Saturday morning, we’re publishing “This Week in the 2020 Race”: a quick way to catch up on the presidential campaign and the field of 24 candidates for the Democratic nomination. Here’s our latest edition:

abstract: The anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany wants to know the nationalities of artists employed by state theaters, and cultural organizations are worried.
snippet: The anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany wants to know the nationalities of artists employed by state theaters, and cultural organizations are worried.
lead_paragraph: STUTTGART, Germany — Elliott Carlton Hines, a baritone who sings with the Stuttgart State Opera, received a text message in June that unnerved him. A friend was telling him that the state culture ministry had been asked for the nationalities of artists employed in the state-funded opera, orchestra and ballet companies, as well as where they had been educated.

abstract: “I think it scares people,” Gov. Michelle Lujan Grisham of New Mexico said of a proposal to eliminate private health insurance. Other governors echoed similar concerns.
snippet: “I think it scares people,” Gov. Michelle Lujan Grisham of New Mexico said of a proposal to eliminate private health insurance. Other governors echoed similar concerns.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After claiming governorships from Republicans in seven states last year, including in crucial presidential battlegrounds like Wisconsin and Michigan, Democratic governors should have good reason to celebrate.
